The paper deals with optimization problems involving probabilistic constraints and decision-making under uncertainty, which are common themes in several sub-fields of computer science. The use of submodular functions and matroids suggests a connection to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and combinatorial optimization (cs.GT). The mention of adaptive vs non-adaptive strategies and the use of probability distributions over multiple values suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.AI) and statistical learning theory (cs.LG). Finally, the analysis of worst-case adaptivity gaps involves techniques from information theory (cs.IT).
